window.MC_CLIFF_NOTES = {
  "1": "The merchant ship Pharaon returns to Marseilles, and young first mate Edmond Dantès reports to owner Morrel that Captain Leclere died during the voyage, though the cargo is intact. Dantès mentions he made an unscheduled stop at Elba to fulfill the dying captain's request and briefly met Napoleon there. Morrel is pleased with Dantès's conduct and considers making him captain, while the ship's supercargo, Danglars, quietly tries to cast suspicion on him. Dantès declines an invitation to dinner so he can hurry to see his father and then his fiancée, Mercédès.",
  "2": "Dantès rushes to see his elderly father and discovers the old man secretly went hungry while he was away in order to repay a debt to their neighbor Caderousse. Dantès gives his father money and promises a better future. Caderousse arrives and feigns warm friendship while masking envy. After Dantès leaves for the Catalan village, Caderousse meets Danglars, and the two gossip about Dantès's good fortune and a Catalan cousin of Mercédès who may resent his return.",
  "3": "At the Catalan village, Fernand begs Mercédès to marry him, but she firmly refuses, insisting she loves only Edmond. Dantès arrives and is welcomed joyfully by Mercédès, causing tense hostility between him and Fernand that Mercédès manages to defuse. A shaken Fernand storms off and encounters Danglars and a drunken Caderousse at a tavern, where Danglars begins probing Fernand's jealousy over losing Mercédès.",
  "4": "Danglars manipulates the desperate Fernand, proposing that having Dantès imprisoned (rather than killed) would separate him from Mercédès without provoking her vow to die if Edmond were harmed. Danglars drafts a disguised, anonymous letter denouncing Dantès as a courier for Bonapartist conspirators. He pretends to discard the letter and leaves with the very drunk Caderousse, not realizing Fernand secretly retrieves the crumpled note.",
  "5": "Dantès and Mercédès's wedding feast takes place at La Réserve, attended by Morrel, who confirms Dantès will soon be made captain. Fernand looks visibly tormented throughout the celebration. Just as the couple is about to leave for the marriage ceremony, a magistrate and soldiers arrive and arrest Dantès on suspicion of being a Bonapartist agent, plunging the gathering into shock and grief.",
  "6": "At a separate engagement dinner in Marseilles, the ambitious young deputy prosecutor Gérard de Villefort discusses politics with his royalist future in-laws and boasts of his severity toward conspirators. He is abruptly called away on business and returns having read an anonymous denunciation, revealing to the gathered guests that a suspected Bonapartist plot has just been uncovered — on the very day of his own betrothal.",
  "7": "Villefort interrogates Dantès, who calmly and honestly explains Captain Leclere's dying request, his stop at Elba, and his brief exchange with Napoleon. Sympathetic at first and inclined to release him, Villefort grows alarmed upon learning the letter Dantès unknowingly carried is addressed to a man named Noirtier — his own father. He burns the letter, swears Dantès to secrecy about ever having seen it, then unexpectedly has him detained rather than freed.",
  "8": "Dantès is taken by boat through Marseilles harbor and realizes with horror that he is being delivered not to freedom but to the grim island prison, the Château d'If. He attempts a desperate leap into the sea but is restrained by his guards. Thrown into a dark dungeon, he pleads to see the governor, and after threatening a jailer in his desperation, he is moved to an even harsher cell below.",
  "9": "Villefort hastily secures his own finances and prepares to travel to Paris, advising his future father-in-law to sell his investments given the growing political crisis. Outside his home, a distraught Mercédès begs him for news of Edmond, but Villefort coldly claims he can do nothing for him, though he privately feels the first pangs of guilt as he departs.",
  "10": "In Paris, Villefort reports to King Louis XVIII about the supposed Bonapartist conspiracy he uncovered, earning royal praise and a medal for his vigilance. Before he can leave, urgent news arrives that Napoleon has actually escaped Elba and landed in France, throwing the royal court into alarm.",
  "11": "The king and his ministers react with dismay as reports confirm Napoleon is advancing through France largely unopposed. Villefort tactfully secures his own standing amid the chaos, and a separate investigation into a recent murder mentions a suspect whose description unsettlingly resembles Villefort's own father. Returning to his lodgings, Villefort finds an unexpected visitor waiting for him.",
  "12": "Villefort's mysterious visitor turns out to be his father, Noirtier, an active Bonapartist implicated in the very killing under investigation. Villefort warns him of the danger he's in, and Noirtier calmly disguises his appearance using items borrowed from his son's room before slipping away, confidently predicting Napoleon's unstoppable return to power.",
  "13": "As Napoleon's brief return to power unfolds, Villefort loses his position and focuses on protecting his fugitive father rather than helping Dantès, despite repeated pleas from Morrel. Political upheaval, Napoleon's final defeat, and the second restoration follow in quick succession, and Dantès remains forgotten in his cell while Danglars flees the country, Fernand is conscripted into the army, and Dantès's elderly father dies of grief and privation.",
  "14": "A year later, a prison inspector visits the Château d'If, and Dantès — now referred to only as a number — passionately begs for a trial, but is turned away once officials learn of the serious political charge against him. The inspector also visits a nearby cell holding an eccentric elderly prisoner, the Abbé Faria, who offers a vast fortune for his freedom and is dismissed as a harmless madman.",
  "15": "Worn down after years of imprisonment, Dantès resolves to starve himself to death, but a mysterious scratching noise from within his cell wall reawakens his will to live. After cautiously communicating with the source through taps on the wall, he begins digging toward it and eventually breaks through to discover that another prisoner has been tunneling in his direction.",
  "16": "Dantès meets the source of the tunneling, the learned Abbé Faria, who explains that his escape route led to the wrong place and recounts his years of remarkable self-taught achievements in captivity, including homemade tools, ink, and paper. The two quickly form a close bond, and Faria begins sharing his vast knowledge with his young companion.",
  "17": "In Faria's cell, Dantès marvels at the abbé's ingenious handmade possessions, including a rope ladder and pens fashioned from fish bones. Using careful logical reasoning, Faria helps Dantès piece together that Danglars and Fernand conspired against him, and reveals that the \"Noirtier\" named in the fatal letter was Villefort's own father — a discovery that fills Dantès with fury. Afterward, Faria begins tutoring Dantès in earnest across many subjects.",
  "18": "Faria reveals to Dantès the story of an immense hidden fortune, detailed in an old will he deciphered years earlier, once belonging to the extinct Spada family and tied to a Renaissance-era poisoning plot. He explains that the treasure lies hidden on the island of Monte Cristo and names Dantès as his heir to half of it, treating him as the son he never had.",
  "19": "The two prisoners continue their studies and friendship while planning an eventual escape, but a repair project seals off the route they had painstakingly dug toward the sea. One night Faria suffers a sudden, severe attack of paralysis; Dantès revives him with a prepared remedy, and the weakened abbé makes Dantès memorize the treasure's exact location and swear to pursue it.",
  "20": "Faria soon suffers a final, fatal attack and dies in Dantès's arms. Overwhelmed by grief and facing the prospect of endless solitary confinement, Dantès conceives a desperate plan: he takes the dead man's place inside the burial sack, hoping to be thrown into the sea rather than buried, and that night guards indeed cast him from the fortress into the water with a heavy weight tied to his feet.",
  "21": "Dantès frees himself underwater just before drowning and swims through a raging storm to reach a small barren island. The next morning he swims out to intercept a passing smuggling vessel, invents a story about surviving a shipwreck, and is taken aboard, discovering to his shock that fourteen years have passed since his imprisonment began.",
  "22": "Dantès earns the trust of his new smuggler companions through his sailing skill, adopting an assumed identity and forming a friendship with a sailor named Jacopo. He glimpses the island of Monte Cristo during a voyage but cannot yet investigate it, survives a wound during a skirmish with customs officers, and eventually learns that the crew's next job will take them to Monte Cristo itself.",
  "23": "Upon reaching Monte Cristo with the smugglers, Dantès feigns a serious injury from a fall so that his companions will leave him behind alone on the island while they sail off to conduct other business, giving him the solitude he has long awaited.",
  "24": "Left alone on Monte Cristo, Dantès locates the marked spot described in Faria's will, uses gunpowder to blast open a hidden rock formation, and discovers a concealed cave. Digging where instructed, he unearths an ancient chest overflowing with gold, jewels, and treasure exactly as Faria had described.",
  "25": "Dantès conceals part of the treasure, rejoins the smugglers, and begins easing his way out of that life, rewarding his friend Jacopo generously and purchasing a private yacht with secret compartments. He returns to Monte Cristo to collect his fortune, then sails to Marseilles under a new identity, where he learns his father has died and Mercédès has disappeared; he quietly visits his father's old home and the Catalan village without revealing himself, leaving generous gifts before slipping away.",
  "26": "Years later, the once-cheerful Caderousse now runs a struggling roadside inn with his sickly wife. A mysterious Italian priest arrives and asks about Edmond Dantès, eventually revealing that Dantès died in prison and left instructions for a valuable diamond to be divided among several old friends and his father.",
  "27": "Caderousse recounts to the priest the full story of Dantès's downfall, admitting his own passive role in staying silent, and reveals that Danglars and Fernand have both risen to wealth and status while Mercédès, now married to Fernand, lives in high society but seems unhappy, and that old Dantès died from grief and neglect. Moved by the account, the priest gives the entire diamond to Caderousse alone, in exchange for an old purse that had once belonged to Morrel.",
  "28": "An Englishman representing the banking house of Thomson & French investigates the failing fortunes of shipowner Morrel and buys up a debt owed to a prison inspector. In return for the favor, he examines the Château d'If's prison records concerning Dantès and Faria, uncovering the full truth of Villefort's role in the case and discreetly pocketing incriminating documents.",
  "29": "Morrel's shipping business teeters on total collapse, and the mysterious Englishman visits him just as news arrives that Morrel's last hope, the ship Pharaon, has been lost at sea with everyone assuming the cargo gone. The Englishman unexpectedly grants Morrel a three-month extension on his debts and cryptically tells Morrel's daughter Julie to await further instructions from someone signing himself \"Sinbad the Sailor.\"",
  "30": "As the extension nears its end with no way to cover his debts, Morrel resolves to take his own life to preserve his family's honor, having secured his son's reluctant promise to carry on afterward. At the last possible moment, his daughter Julie arrives with a purse containing the exact funds needed and a valuable diamond, delivered according to mysterious instructions, and word comes that the Pharaon has miraculously reached port after all, saving the family from ruin.",
  "31": "Franz d'Épinay, waiting in Florence before joining his friend Albert de Morcerf in Rome, takes a boat trip to the tiny island of Monte Cristo to hunt goats. There he learns the island is used by smugglers and meets its mysterious owner, a wealthy, deathly pale man who calls himself Sinbad the Sailor and lives in a lavishly furnished grotto. Sinbad hosts Franz to an opulent supper and introduces him to hashish, and Franz spends the night lost in a vivid, sensuous drug-induced dream filled with statues coming to life.",
  "32": "Franz wakes alone in the grotto to find his mysterious host already gone by yacht, leaving only a wave of farewell and a cannon shot in parting. Unable to find any trace of the hidden entrance to the grotto despite searching, Franz sails on to Rome to meet Albert, arriving to find the city crowded for Carnival and lodging scarce. He and Albert learn from their innkeeper, Signor Pastrini, that no carriages or windows can be had for the festivities.",
  "33": "Franz and Albert secure a carriage from Pastrini for an exorbitant price and set out sightseeing. Over dinner, Pastrini warns them that their planned route to the Colosseum is dangerous because of the notorious bandit Luigi Vampa, and tells them Vampa's life story: a gifted shepherd boy in love with a girl named Teresa who, after Teresa is nearly abducted by the vicious bandit chief Cucumetto, shoots Cucumetto dead and is elected the new chief in his place. Franz is startled to hear that years earlier a traveler calling himself Sinbad the Sailor once gave Vampa a rich gift on the road.",
  "34": "Franz and Albert tour the Colosseum by moonlight, where Franz secretly overhears a cloaked stranger arranging with a Roman bandit to save a condemned man named Peppino from execution, and recognizes the stranger's voice as that of his host from Monte Cristo. That night at the opera, Franz sees the same pale man again in a box with a beautiful veiled Greek woman, confirming to himself that this is the same mysterious figure, while the superstitious Countess G declares he must be a vampire. The next day, the young men learn that their neighbor at the hotel is the fabulously wealthy Count of Monte Cristo, who has offered them the use of his carriage and windows for the Carnival.",
  "35": "Franz and Albert call on the Count of Monte Cristo, who receives them graciously and reveals a cold, philosophical fascination with punishment and revenge as they discuss the day's scheduled executions. At the appointed hour they watch from the count's window as Peppino is pardoned at the last moment through the count's secret intervention, but the other condemned man, Andrea, is brutally put to death by the mace and knife of the executioner. Franz and Albert are horrified by the spectacle, while the count watches with eerie composure.",
  "36": "As soon as the execution ends, the Piazza del Popolo transforms into the riotous celebration of Carnival, and Franz, Albert, and the count don costumes and join the chaos of confetti, flowers, and masked revelers. Albert becomes infatuated with a masked peasant girl who throws him a bouquet from a passing carriage, and arranges an anonymous rendezvous with her for the last night of Carnival. The festivities culminate in the traditional moccoli, where everyone tries to light and extinguish each other's candles, and Albert follows his mysterious admirer into the crowd just as the celebration ends.",
  "37": "Franz waits anxiously when Albert fails to return from his rendezvous, and eventually receives a letter revealing that Albert has been captured by Luigi Vampa's bandits and held for ransom, with a threat to kill him if the money isn't paid by morning. Franz turns to the Count of Monte Cristo, who calmly summons Vampa's messenger and agrees to accompany Franz to the bandits' hideout in the catacombs of St. Sebastian rather than simply pay the ransom. There, Vampa apologizes profusely for having unknowingly kidnapped a friend of the count's, and Albert, found calmly asleep in captivity, is released unharmed.",
  "38": "The next morning, Albert warmly thanks Monte Cristo for his rescue and, wanting to repay the favor, invites the count to visit him in Paris, and the two men formally set an appointment for three months later. Franz privately confesses to Albert his suspicion that the count is the same man he encountered at Monte Cristo and at the Colosseum, recounting the whole strange history, but Albert good-naturedly dismisses his friend's unease as needless mystery-making. The two young men then part ways, Albert for Paris and Franz for Venice.",
  "39": "Months later in Paris, Albert de Morcerf prepares an elegant breakfast at his home to receive the Count of Monte Cristo as promised. Before the count arrives, Albert's fashionable friends gather, including the secretary Lucien Debray, the journalist Beauchamp, the aristocratic Château-Renaud, and Captain Maximilian Morrel, whom Château-Renaud introduces as the man who once saved his life in Africa. As they wait and gossip about the mysterious count, whom Albert has been describing in fantastic terms, the count arrives punctually at the stroke of the appointed hour.",
  "40": "Over breakfast, the count captivates the gathered young men with tales of his travels, his abstemious eating habits, and a demonstration of his hashish-and-opium pills carried in a hollowed emerald. When Albert credits the count with rescuing him from bandits, Monte Cristo explains his long-standing acquaintance with Vampa, and the conversation touches on Albert's likely engagement to Eugénie Danglars. Maximilian Morrel is visibly startled when the count mentions his bankers, Thomson & French of Rome, the same firm that once did the Morrel family an unexplained kindness.",
  "41": "Albert shows the count around his family's house and introduces him to his father, the Comte de Morcerf, and mother, Mercédès. The count notices a portrait of Mercédès dressed as a Catalan fisherwoman and remarks strangely on a sense of having met her before, unsettling both the countess and Albert's father. Mercédès receives the count with visible emotion and pallor, and afterward questions Albert closely and anxiously about who this fascinating, unsettling stranger really is.",
  "42": "Back at his own Paris residence, Monte Cristo directs his steward Bertuccio in various errands, including arranging for a notary to finalize the purchase of a country house he bought sight unseen based on a newspaper advertisement. When the notary reveals the house is in Auteuil, Bertuccio turns pale with obvious dread, though he tries to hide it. The count, suspicious, insists that Bertuccio accompany him personally to inspect the new property that evening.",
  "43": "At the house in Auteuil, Bertuccio grows increasingly terrified as they explore the grounds, particularly the garden, which he seems to recognize with horror. Pressed by the count, who threatens to dismiss him unless he explains himself, Bertuccio reveals that this very garden was the scene of an assassination he once committed, targeting a man who turns out to have been the father-in-law of the former king's attorney Villefort. Intrigued, Monte Cristo settles down to hear Bertuccio's full confession.",
  "44": "Bertuccio recounts how his brother was murdered in Nîmes and how the callous young prosecutor Villefort refused to pursue justice, prompting Bertuccio to swear a vendetta against him. Trailing Villefort to a secret rendezvous house in Auteuil, Bertuccio stabbed him in the garden just as Villefort was burying a small box, which turned out to contain a newborn infant that Villefort had believed dead; Bertuccio revived the child and left him at a Paris foundling hospital, and his sister Assunta later reclaimed and raised the boy, who grew into a troubled young man named Benedetto. Bertuccio also begins recounting an unrelated tale of visiting an innkeeper named Caderousse, who was persuaded by his wife to sell a valuable diamond to a visiting jeweler.",
  "45": "The jeweler, having agreed to purchase the diamond from Caderousse and his ailing wife La Carconte for a large sum, is persuaded by a raging storm to stay the night at their inn. Bertuccio, hiding nearby, later hears gunshots and cries, and creeping into the house finds La Carconte dead on the stairs and the jeweler stabbed to death in his room, with Caderousse having fled with the money and diamond. Bertuccio is discovered at the scene covered in blood and immediately arrested by custom-house officers as the presumed murderer.",
  "46": "Bertuccio concludes his story, explaining that the Abbé Busoni intervened to secure his release after Caderousse was later caught and confessed, sentencing him to the galleys, and that the abbé then recommended Bertuccio into Monte Cristo's service; he also reveals that his sister's adopted son Benedetto later turned violently on her, an event Bertuccio views as just punishment for his own past sins. Having absolved Bertuccio of guilt in his own way, the count turns to establishing himself in Paris, calling on the banker Danglars and coolly demonstrating that his letters of credit are effectively unlimited, thoroughly unsettling the pompous banker.",
  "47": "The count visits Madame Danglars and, through a series of maneuvers, ends up purchasing her prized carriage horses from her husband without her knowledge, then returns them to her adorned with diamonds as a gift, embarrassing Danglars in front of his wife. Later, while the count is testing his Nubian servant Ali's skill with a lasso, the same pair of horses bolt out of control pulling a carriage carrying Madame de Villefort and her young son Edward; Ali daringly stops the runaway horses, and the count brings the shaken mother and child into his home to recover, meeting Madame de Villefort for the first time.",
  "48": "Monsieur de Villefort, the reserved and ambitious royal prosecutor, calls on Monte Cristo to formally thank him for saving his wife and son. Their conversation turns into an unusual philosophical debate, with the count expounding startling, grandiose ideas about providence, fate, and his own sense of being an instrument of a higher justice, leaving Villefort both fascinated and unsettled. Villefort mentions his paralyzed father Noirtier and his two children, Valentine and Edward, contrasting the old man's helplessness with the vitality of the young.",
  "49": "The count spends time with Haydée, the beautiful young Greek woman living under his protection in richly appointed apartments in his Paris house. Their tender conversation reveals her deep devotion and love for him, her memories of her father, and her willingness to remain hidden from society and follow him anywhere, though the count insists she is technically free to leave him if she wishes.",
  "50": "Monte Cristo visits the modest but happy household of Maximilian Morrel, his sister Julie, and her husband Emmanuel, admiring their contentment despite giving up their once-larger shipping fortune. Julie shows him a treasured purse and letter, kept under glass, from an anonymous benefactor who years ago saved their father Morrel from ruin and suicide, signed only \"Sinbad the Sailor.\" When Maximilian recalls his father's dying words identifying the benefactor as a man named Edmond Dantès, the count is overcome with emotion and abruptly excuses himself.",
  "51": "In a secluded corner of the Villefort garden, Maximilian Morrel and Valentine de Villefort meet secretly through a gate, having fallen in love despite Valentine's expected engagement to Franz d'Épinay. Valentine describes her unhappy home life, neglected by her father and resented by her stepmother, who favors her own son Edward, and confides that her only real comfort is her paralyzed grandfather Noirtier. Their meeting is cut short when Valentine is called away to receive an unexpected visitor, the Count of Monte Cristo.",
  "52": "Monte Cristo calls on Madame de Villefort to return her husband's earlier visit, meeting her son Edward and stepdaughter Valentine and recalling, to Madame de Villefort's visible unease, a previous chance meeting with her in Italy. Their conversation turns to poisons and chemistry, with the count expounding at unsettling length and expertise on undetectable methods of poisoning, gradual immunity to toxins, and untraceable \"eliminations,\" a subject Madame de Villefort pursues with keen, almost eager interest. He leaves her a recipe for a supposed remedy, warning that in a larger dose it would be lethal.",
  "53": "At the opera, Parisian society gossips about the Count of Monte Cristo's exploits, including an anonymous horse named Vampa that won a race and a valuable cup sent to Countess G. Albert and his circle discuss Eugénie Danglars, and the count appears with Haydée, whose beauty draws every eye. When the Comte de Morcerf enters and Haydée catches sight of his face beside the count's, she recoils in horror, later telling Monte Cristo that Morcerf betrayed and sold her father to the Turks, the source of the fortune he now enjoys.",
  "54": "Albert visits the count to thank him again and discusses his lukewarm feelings about his likely marriage to Eugénie Danglars, which his mother strongly opposes, while Lucien Debray casually reveals the scale of Danglars' stock speculation profits. The count proposes hosting a dinner at his house in Auteuil for the Danglars and Villefort families, and tactfully arranges for Albert and his parents to have a pretext to be absent so as not to create the appearance of a matchmaking scheme. The count also mentions expecting a Major Cavalcanti and his son to Paris society.",
  "55": "An anxious, shabbily but respectably dressed Italian calling himself Major Bartolomeo Cavalcanti arrives at the count's house, having been sent by the Abbé Busoni with a letter promising him money and reunion with a long-lost son. Monte Cristo coaches the confused but greedy major through the details of his supposed backstory, supplies him with forged documents proving his identity and his son's birth, gives him cash, and advises him on proper dress, all while the major eagerly accepts each new fabricated detail.",
  "56": "The count then meets the \"son,\" a polished young man calling himself Andrea Cavalcanti, and privately observes through a hidden peephole as father and son are reunited. Once alone, the two frauds candidly compare the letters that summoned each of them to Paris, signed respectively by the Abbé Busoni and by \"Sinbad the Sailor,\" and realize neither knows who is truly orchestrating this scheme or why, though both are content to play along for the money offered. The count then formally introduces the pair to society and invites them to his upcoming dinner at Auteuil.",
  "57": "Maximilian waits in the garden for Valentine, who is delayed by a visit from Eugénie Danglars; the two young women have been commiserating over their unwanted engagements. Maximilian tells Valentine of his growing, almost superstitious sense that the Count of Monte Cristo has been secretly guiding his fortunes for good, citing an uncanny series of coincidences, though Valentine confesses the count seems to pointedly ignore her and has never shown her any particular warmth.",
  "58": "Villefort and his wife inform the paralyzed Noirtier that Valentine is to marry Franz d'Épinay, provoking violent, wordless fury from the old man, who clearly disapproves. After they leave, Valentine comes to comfort her grandfather and, through their private system of eye-signal communication, learns that he objects strongly to the marriage; Noirtier then insists, over Villefort's objections, on summoning a notary immediately.",
  "59": "With Valentine's patient help interpreting his eye movements, Noirtier manages to communicate his wishes to a notary and dictate a will despite being unable to speak or move. To the family's shock, he disinherits Valentine of her entire 900,000-franc fortune specifically because she is going through with the marriage to Franz d'Épinay, redirecting the money to charity instead, while making clear he still loves her deeply. Villefort declares that the marriage will proceed regardless of the financial loss.",
  "60": "The Count of Monte Cristo visits the Villefort household and finds Villefort openly bitter and Madame de Villefort quietly pleased about Noirtier's will disinheriting Valentine. Their conversation reveals that Noirtier's hatred of the d'Épinay family stems from old political enmity, as Noirtier was a fervent Jacobin conspirator against the Bourbons while Franz's father, Baron d'Épinay, was a royalist assassinated years earlier. Monte Cristo also learns, unsettling Villefort, that the count's new Auteuil house once belonged to the Saint-Méran family, before departing on a whimsical errand to observe a telegraph tower out of pure curiosity.",
  "61": "Monte Cristo visits a telegraph operator near Montlhéry and learns the man's one passion is gardening on his tiny plot. Playing on the operator's love of his garden, Monte Cristo bribes him with a fortune to transmit a false signal claiming Don Carlos has fled to Spain. The false report panics Danglars into dumping his Spanish bonds, and when the news is retracted the next day he loses nearly a million francs, all while remaining unaware of the trick.",
  "62": "Monte Cristo hosts his first dinner party at his newly and lavishly redecorated house in Auteuil, welcoming the Danglars, the Villeforts, the Cavalcantis, and others. While counting guests, his steward Bertuccio is thunderstruck to recognize Madame Danglars and Villefort, whom he thought he had killed years earlier in that same garden, and also recognizes young Andrea Cavalcanti as someone from his past. Monte Cristo calms the shaken Bertuccio and the dinner proceeds.",
  "63": "Over an extravagant meal, Monte Cristo dazzles his guests with stories of rare delicacies and philosophy. Afterward he leads several of them, including Villefort and Madame Danglars, to see an old red-draped room he finds strangely oppressive, unsettling both of them with talk of unspoken tragedy. In the garden he then casually reveals that his workers recently dug up a small box containing an infant's skeleton, visibly shaking Villefort and Madame Danglars.",
  "64": "As the dinner guests depart, Villefort quietly arranges a private meeting with Madame Danglars for the next day. Driving home afterward, Andrea Cavalcanti is accosted by a ragged stranger who turns out to be Caderousse, recognizing him by his true name; Caderousse extracts money and a promise of a monthly allowance from Andrea before slipping away near the city gates.",
  "65": "Madame Danglars returns home escorted by Debray, who presses her about her strange agitation at the count's dinner, which she deflects. Her husband Danglars unexpectedly asserts himself, dismissing Debray and confronting his wife over recent stock losses he blames on her speculation and her ties to Debray. In a cold, calculated speech he reveals he has long known of her infidelities, including a veiled reference to a past connection with Villefort.",
  "66": "Danglars visits Monte Cristo to complain about his financial losses and to discuss business with the Cavalcantis. Their conversation turns to Danglars's marriage plans for his daughter Eugénie, weighing Albert de Morcerf against Andrea Cavalcanti, and Danglars voices contempt for Morcerf's father, hinting at disgraceful secrets from his past as a fisherman named Fernand. At Monte Cristo's suggestion, Danglars decides to write to a contact in Yanina for more information.",
  "67": "Madame Danglars meets Villefort privately at his office, where he finally confesses the full truth he had hidden from her: their infant, whom he believed dead, was actually alive when he buried it years earlier and vanished after he was stabbed that same night. He recounts his fruitless later search for the child through a foundling hospital, and the two grow fearful that Monte Cristo somehow knows their secret.",
  "68": "Albert visits Monte Cristo, and they discuss Andrea Cavalcanti's courtship of Eugénie Danglars and Albert's own reluctance about marrying her. Albert invites Monte Cristo to an upcoming summer ball at his parents' house, and the count agrees after learning Albert's mother, the Countess Mercédès, wishes it. Afterward, Monte Cristo learns from Bertuccio that Madame Danglars spent time at the law courts that day.",
  "69": "Villefort has the police quietly investigate Monte Cristo's background, and an agent interviews both the Abbé Busoni and Lord Wilmore, unaware both are disguises worn by the count himself. The two invented characters give vague, sometimes contradictory accounts of Monte Cristo's origins and wealth, including a claim that he intends to build a charitable institution or spa at his Auteuil house. Villefort ends the day only partly reassured.",
  "70": "At the Morcerfs' summer ball, Monte Cristo mingles among the assembled guests, including the Danglars family, the Cavalcantis, and Albert's parents, trading gossip and witty commentary. Albert introduces Maximilian Morrel to Madame de Villefort, and Morrel exchanges a silent, meaningful look with Valentine across the room. Noticing that Monte Cristo refuses to eat or drink anything in her house, the Countess Mercédès grows troubled and asks him to walk with her in the garden.",
  "71": "In the garden, Mercédès urges Monte Cristo to share fruit with her as a gesture of friendship, but he pointedly and repeatedly declines. She questions him gently about his past and whether he has ever loved, and he tells her, without revealing his identity, of a lost love in Malta who married another while he was away. Their conversation is cut short when Albert brings news that Madame de Saint-Méran has arrived with word of her husband's sudden death, breaking up the ball.",
  "72": "At the Villefort house, the grieving Madame de Saint-Méran describes her husband's sudden apparent apoplectic death during their journey to Paris. Despite the mourning, she insists Valentine's marriage to Franz d'Épinay be hurried along, and later describes a frightening vision of a ghostly figure in her sickroom. The family doctor, d'Avrigny, is called in to attend to her feverish, agitated condition.",
  "73": "At the garden gate, Valentine tells Maximilian that her grandmother's arrival has pushed for a swift marriage to Franz, who has now reached Paris. Morrel proposes they run away together, but Valentine refuses to defy her family outright, instead promising to resist the marriage as long as she can and to flee with him only if the contract is actually signed. That night, hiding nearby, Morrel overhears Dr. d'Avrigny confide to Villefort his strong suspicion that Madame de Saint-Méran was poisoned.",
  "74": "A double funeral is held for the Marquis and Marquise de Saint-Méran, attended by Albert, Beauchamp, Château-Renaud, Franz, and Morrel, who discuss the family's fortune and the string of sudden deaths. Afterward, Villefort presses Franz to proceed at once with signing the marriage contract despite the recent deaths, and Franz agrees. At the signing, the notary reveals that Noirtier has disinherited Valentine over the match, but Noirtier then unexpectedly insists on speaking privately with Franz.",
  "75": "In Noirtier's room, the old man directs Valentine to a hidden document, which turns out to be a sworn account of a secret political meeting on the night Franz's father was killed years ago. Franz reads aloud how the gathering forced his royalist father into a duel after he refused to support their cause, ending in the father's death at the hands of the group's president. When Franz demands to know who that president was, Noirtier reveals, spelling it out letter by letter, that it was himself.",
  "76": "Andrea Cavalcanti continues to rise in Parisian society as Danglars's favored suitor for Eugénie, and the two visit the Danglars home together with Monte Cristo also present. Albert arrives and treats Eugénie with pointed indifference, further encouraging Danglars toward Andrea. Danglars asks Monte Cristo to formally raise the marriage question with the Morcerf family, and separately receives unsettling news from a courier he had sent to investigate matters in Greece.",
  "77": "Riding home with Albert, Monte Cristo is teased about Andrea's courtship of Eugénie. Back at his house, Albert asks to meet Haydée, and Monte Cristo agrees on the condition Albert never reveal the meeting or mention that his own father once served in the region she comes from. Haydée then recounts to Albert her childhood memories of her father Ali Tepelini's court, the siege that led to his downfall and death at the hands of an unnamed traitor, and her own enslavement afterward, ending with how Monte Cristo purchased and freed her.",
  "78": "Franz formally ends his engagement to Valentine after Noirtier's revelation, and Madame de Villefort persuades Noirtier to restore Valentine's inheritance, which he does. Meanwhile Danglars coldly refuses Morcerf's request for Albert to marry Eugénie, hinting at damaging rumors without explaining, which humiliates the elder Morcerf. That same morning Albert learns from Monte Cristo that he must fight a duel with Beauchamp over an insulting newspaper item concerning a Colonel Fernand.",
  "79": "Morrel is summoned to Noirtier's room, where Valentine relays her grandfather's plan to move with her into a new home, so that she may eventually marry Morrel once she comes of age with his blessing. During the visit, the elderly servant Barrois suddenly falls violently ill after drinking from Noirtier's usual lemonade, and dies despite Dr. d'Avrigny's efforts. The doctor privately confirms through a chemical test that the lemonade had been poisoned.",
  "80": "Dr. d'Avrigny tells Villefort he is now certain a poisoner is at work in the household, responsible for the deaths of the Saint-Mérans and the attempt on Noirtier that killed Barrois by accident instead. Reasoning from motive and opportunity, he concludes that Valentine is the culprit and urges Villefort to act, but the horrified father refuses to believe or expose his daughter. The two reach an uneasy truce in which the doctor agrees to silence for now, and the household's servants quit en masse out of fear.",
  "81": "Andrea Cavalcanti formally asks Danglars for Eugénie's hand, and the two discuss fortunes and dowries with Danglars's happy approval. Later, Caderousse summons Andrea to his lodgings, extracts a larger monthly allowance from him, and presses him with questions about Monte Cristo's Paris house, getting Andrea to sketch its layout under the pretense of curiosity, including the location of a valuable cabinet and the count's planned absence at Auteuil.",
  "82": "Monte Cristo receives an anonymous letter warning that someone plans to break into his Paris house that night. He sends his household away but secretly stays behind armed with Ali, and catches the intruder in the act, revealing him to be Caderousse in disguise. After interrogating him and learning that Andrea Cavalcanti is really an escaped convict called Benedetto, Monte Cristo forces Caderousse to write and sign a letter exposing this to Danglars, then lets him leave, only for an unseen figure to stab him as he climbs down outside.",
  "83": "The mortally wounded Caderousse is carried inside by Monte Cristo, who confirms his attacker was Benedetto. Still believing he is speaking to the priest Abbé Busoni, Caderousse dictates and signs a deathbed statement naming Benedetto as his murderer. As he dies, Monte Cristo reveals more of his true face and voice, and Caderousse senses his real identity just before expiring in a moment of terrified repentance.",
  "84": "Paris buzzes over the failed robbery and Caderousse's murder while preparations continue for Andrea and Eugénie's wedding. Beauchamp, having spent weeks quietly investigating in Yanina, returns and privately confirms to Albert that the newspaper accusation against a treacherous Colonel Fernand is true and refers to Albert's own father; out of friendship he destroys his evidence, leaving a devastated Albert to face the truth alone.",
  "85": "Monte Cristo, Albert, and Beauchamp believe the Yanina rumor has quietly died down, and Monte Cristo invites Albert on a sudden trip to his Normandy estate to take his mind off things. During their stay, a courier arrives with news that a second newspaper has published the accusation naming Albert's father outright as the Count of Morcerf, prompting a shaken Albert to rush back to Paris alone.",
  "86": "Beauchamp describes to Albert how the Chamber of Peers held an inquiry into Morcerf's conduct at Yanina, where the count at first defended himself convincingly with documents and testimony. A mysterious veiled witness was then admitted and revealed herself as Haydée, who produced proof that Morcerf, then known as Fernand, betrayed her father Ali Pasha, sold her and her mother into slavery, and profited from it; the assembly formally condemns Morcerf as he flees the chamber in disgrace.",
  "87": "Distraught, Albert vows to confront whoever exposed his father and enlists Beauchamp's help. Beauchamp reveals that Danglars had written to Yanina for information at Monte Cristo's suggestion, so the two confront Danglars, who admits writing the letter but denies personal malice, shifting all blame to the count. Albert leaves convinced that Monte Cristo orchestrated the entire exposure and resolves to seek him out directly.",
  "88": "Albert tracks Monte Cristo down at the Opera and publicly insults him before witnesses, throwing down a challenge that the count calmly accepts, privately telling a friend he intends to kill Albert. Before the encounter, Albert visits his distressed mother Mercédès, hinting darkly at Monte Cristo without naming him, and she begs him not to treat the count as an enemy. Terms for a pistol duel the next morning are arranged through Beauchamp.",
  "89": "That night Mercédès secretly visits Monte Cristo and, calling him by his old name, reveals she has long recognized him and begs him to spare her son. In anguish, Monte Cristo finally confirms his identity to her and recounts how her husband's betrayal led to his imprisonment and his father's death, explaining the depth of his vengeance. Moved by her plea, he agrees to spare Albert, though he privately resolves not to defend himself in the coming duel.",
  "90": "Monte Cristo spends a sleepless night revising his will to provide for Maximilian and Haydée, and Haydée, sensing something is wrong, is left distraught. At the dueling ground the next morning, before any shots are fired, Albert unexpectedly and publicly apologizes to Monte Cristo, acknowledging that his father's past betrayal justified the count's actions and thanking him for his restraint, and the two men shake hands, ending the confrontation.",
  "91": "After Albert publicly apologizes to Monte Cristo and the duel is called off, Albert rides home and, ashamed of his father's dishonor, begins packing to leave with nothing, intending to give up his name and fortune. He finds his mother Mercédès independently doing the same, and the two agree to leave together. A letter arrives from Monte Cristo revealing a personal secret about buried money meant long ago for his own betrothed, which he now offers to Mercédès for her support; she accepts it. As their carriage pulls away from the house, a gunshot is heard from within.",
  "92": "Monte Cristo returns home with Morrel and is joyfully reunited with Haydée, but is soon interrupted by the arrival of the elder Morcerf (Fernand), who has been watching in anguish for his son's return. Fernand angrily challenges Monte Cristo to a duel, taunting him about his mysterious identity, at which point Monte Cristo dramatically reveals himself as Edmond Dantès, the man Fernand betrayed decades earlier. Horrified, Fernand flees home, arriving just in time to see Mercédès and Albert departing forever without a backward glance, and shoots himself as their carriage disappears.",
  "93": "Morrel visits Valentine and Noirtier during their usual quiet hour, and Valentine mentions feeling unwell and increasingly sensitive to the bitter medicine she has been taking in small doses alongside her grandfather's tonic. When Madame Danglars and Eugénie call to formally announce Eugénie's engagement to Andrea Cavalcanti, talk turns to Albert's broken engagement and his father's disgrace. Returning to Noirtier's room afterward, Valentine suddenly grows faint and collapses into a violent seizure in front of a terrified Morrel and Noirtier.",
  "94": "As Villefort rushes for the doctor, Morrel flees to Monte Cristo in a panic, recalling an old conversation he once overheard suggesting that mysterious deaths in the Villefort household were not natural. He confesses that he loves Valentine and begs Monte Cristo to save her, revealing his despair at the thought of losing her. Monte Cristo, visibly shaken, promises Morrel that if Valentine is not already dead, she will live, and sends him home to wait; the doctor d'Avrigny later confirms she has survived a dangerous collapse, crediting Noirtier's mysterious precautions for her survival.",
  "95": "In flashback to earlier that same day, Danglars summons his daughter Eugénie for a formal meeting, where she calmly informs him she has decided not to marry Cavalcanti after all, declaring her wish for an independent, artistic life free of any husband. Danglars admits, with unusual candor, that he needs the marriage to go forward to shore up his shaky finances through a railway investment tied to Cavalcanti's dowry. After extracting a promise that her signature alone is required and her person will remain free, Eugénie coolly agrees to proceed with the contract signing.",
  "96": "As the evening arrives for the signing of Eugénie's marriage contract to Andrea Cavalcanti, the couple's engagement is celebrated amid a lavish gathering at the Danglars mansion, with Monte Cristo among the guests. During the signing, Monte Cristo casually recounts finding a bloodstained waistcoat and an incriminating letter addressed to Danglars among the belongings of the murdered thief Caderousse. Moments later police officers burst in and announce that Andrea Cavalcanti is in fact an escaped convict wanted for Caderousse's murder, and in the ensuing chaos Andrea vanishes from the house.",
  "97": "In the aftermath of the scandal, Eugénie, refusing to be humiliated by another failed engagement, decides to flee Paris rather than face society, using a male disguise and a passport that Monte Cristo had previously and unknowingly helped her obtain for travel abroad. Accompanied by her devoted friend Mademoiselle d'Armilly, she cuts off her hair, packs their savings and jewels, and slips out of the house at night. The two young women depart by post-chaise, successfully making their escape from Paris undetected.",
  "98": "Andrea flees the scene of his exposure, cleverly evading pursuit by cab, on foot, and by hired horse, eventually taking refuge for the night at an inn in Compiègne under a false story. At dawn he discovers gendarmes surrounding the building and attempts to escape up a chimney and across the rooftops, but slips and falls through a chimney into an occupied room, where he is recognized. The room turns out to belong to the fleeing Eugénie and Mademoiselle d'Armilly, and Andrea is captured by the gendarmes moments later.",
  "99": "Madame Danglars, desperate over the scandal and her daughter's flight, first seeks comfort and advice from her lover Debray, who coldly recommends she simply present herself to society as an abandoned, ruined woman. She then appeals to Villefort to show leniency toward Andrea for the family's sake, but Villefort, resolute and severe, insists the law must take its course regardless of personal connections. Word soon arrives that Andrea has been captured at Compiègne, delighting Villefort, who anticipates a sensational trial.",
  "100": "Still weak and feverish from her collapse, Valentine remains under close watch by her father, Noirtier, and a hired nurse, drifting in and out of troubled sleep. Late one night alone in her room, she is startled by a figure emerging silently from a hidden door, who turns out to be Monte Cristo. He reveals that he has secretly rented the house next door and has been watching over her for several nights, testing and adjusting the drinks brought to her room to protect her.",
  "101": "Monte Cristo tells Valentine that someone has been trying to poison her and instructs her to feign sleep so they can observe the culprit together. That night, hidden and pretending to sleep, Valentine watches in horror as her stepmother, Madame de Villefort, quietly pours a substance into her nightly glass before slipping away. Monte Cristo reveals that the killer's motive is to secure Valentine's inheritance for her young half-brother Edward, gives Valentine a special substance to protect her, and extracts her promise to trust him completely no matter what happens next, even swallowing what he provides her.",
  "102": "Later that night, Madame de Villefort returns to check on the effects of the poison and, finding Valentine appearing lifeless, believes her plan has succeeded and quietly withdraws in dread. The next morning the household is thrown into horror when Valentine is discovered apparently dead, and the doctor d'Avrigny, summoned along with Villefort, pronounces her gone. Morrel arrives moments later, having heard the servants' cries, and is devastated to learn that Valentine is dead.",
  "103": "Grief-stricken, Morrel confronts Villefort and, before Noirtier and Doctor d'Avrigny, openly accuses the household of covering up a string of murders, insisting that Valentine was killed and demanding justice. Villefort, cornered by Morrel's certainty and Noirtier's silent confirmation, admits that his father has identified the culprit to him, but begs Morrel and d'Avrigny to swear secrecy, promising he alone will exact a swift and terrible revenge within days. An Italian priest, the Abbé Busoni, arrives to pray over Valentine's body and remains close to the grieving Noirtier.",
  "104": "While Villefort works obsessively to prepare his prosecution of Benedetto as a distraction from his grief, Monte Cristo pays a visit to Danglars and, through a shrewd financial maneuver involving Danglars' boastful credit notes, extracts five million francs from him under the guise of a curious experiment, leaving the banker shaken and unable to refuse. Later that day, as Valentine's funeral arrangements proceed and guests gossip about the run of deaths at the Villefort house, Danglars, secretly ruined and desperate, begins destroying papers, gathering cash, and quietly preparing to abandon his family and flee the country.",
  "105": "Valentine's grand funeral procession makes its way to the cemetery of Père-Lachaise, attended by much of fashionable Paris, while Monte Cristo anxiously searches the crowd for Morrel, whom he eventually finds grieving alone at the grave. Following Morrel home afterward, Monte Cristo breaks in through a window just in time to stop him from shooting himself, and in the ensuing emotional scene reveals his true identity as Edmond Dantès, the family's long-unknown benefactor, overwhelming Morrel, his sister Julie, and her husband Emmanuel with gratitude. Monte Cristo then extracts a solemn promise from Morrel to wait exactly one month, doing nothing rash, before he may be released from that promise.",
  "106": "Danglars flees Paris in secret, leaving behind a bitter letter for his wife blaming her for their financial ruin and declaring their marriage over, while Debray coolly divides their joint speculative profits with Madame Danglars and departs without warmth. Meanwhile, in humble lodgings, Mercédès and Albert tally their small remaining resources; Albert reveals he has sold his valuables and enlisted as a substitute soldier bound for Africa in order to earn money and eventually a name of his own, planning for his mother to live modestly at Marseilles. The two prepare to part ways, encountering Debray by chance as Mercédès departs the city.",
  "107": "Imprisoned in the notorious \"Lions' Den\" section of La Force awaiting trial, Andrea manages to charm and manipulate both fellow prisoners and his jailers with his composure and audacity. He is unexpectedly visited by Bertuccio, who scolds him for his crimes but refuses to reveal who has been secretly protecting and funding him. When Andrea insists on learning his father's true identity, Bertuccio agrees to tell him at a second visit the following day, before their meeting is cut short by the arrival of the examining magistrate.",
  "108": "While obsessively preparing his case against Benedetto, Villefort notices his paralyzed father Noirtier staring with unmistakable hatred toward Madame de Villefort from a window, and grasps his father's silent meaning. That night, after working himself into exhaustion, Villefort confronts his wife directly, coldly revealing that he knows she has poisoned several members of the household, and, to spare the family's name from public disgrace, orders her to take her own life before he returns from the day's court session rather than face the scaffold.",
  "109": "As the sensational trial of Benedetto approaches, all of fashionable Paris buzzes with curiosity and gossip, eager to see the once-celebrated \"Prince Cavalcanti\" now exposed as an escaped convict. Acquaintances speculate wildly about the string of mysterious deaths at the Villefort residence, joking crudely about possible causes, while noting the conspicuous absences of both Monte Cristo and Morrel. The court finally convenes amid a packed and excited crowd.",
  "110": "At the opening of the trial, Andrea unsettles the courtroom by insisting on answering the judge's questions out of the usual order, calmly admitting to being a forger, thief, and murderer. He then stuns the entire assembly by declaring that his father is the presiding prosecutor, M. de Villefort himself, and recounts in precise, damning detail how he was buried alive as an infant and rescued after Villefort was stabbed by an unseen enemy in a garden. Overwhelmed and unable to deny the accusation, Villefort publicly confesses its truth before the horrified court and stumbles out in disgrace, and the session is adjourned.",
  "111": "Shattered by his public disgrace, Villefort rushes home intending to spare his wife, whom he had earlier ordered to kill herself, resolving instead that they should flee together and start anew. But arriving home, he finds she has already poisoned herself, and, searching further, discovers that she has also killed their young son Edward rather than leave him behind, a horror that shatters his mind. In the garden, the enigmatic \"Abbé Busoni\" reveals himself as the Count of Monte Cristo and finally as Edmond Dantès, the man Villefort once wrongfully condemned, leaving the broken, maddened Villefort digging frantically in the earth for a grave that exists only in his ruined imagination.",
  "112": "As Paris reels from the ruin of the Morcerf, Danglars, and Villefort households, Monte Cristo visits Morrel's sister Julie and her husband Emmanuel to collect Maximilian for a journey, offering them an emotional, uncertain farewell. Before departing the city, Monte Cristo pauses on a hilltop overlooking Paris to reflect on his completed mission there with a mixture of pride and quiet foreboding. He and Morrel then travel swiftly toward Marseilles, with Morrel remaining withdrawn and sorrowful throughout the journey.",
  "113": "In Marseilles, Monte Cristo visits Mercédès in the humble house where she now lives alone, and the two share a sorrowful conversation in which she expresses no bitterness toward him despite everything, while he assures her of his continued support for Albert. Monte Cristo then revisits the Château d'If, touring his old dungeon and recovering the manuscript once written by his mentor Abbé Faria, rewarding the guide generously along the way. He finally finds Morrel mourning at his father's grave and secures his renewed promise to meet him at the Island of Monte Cristo on the fifth of October before taking any final, irreversible action.",
  "114": "Danglars, having secretly fled Paris with the last of his fortune, arrives in Rome and visits the banking house of Thomson & French to withdraw a large sum, unaware that he is being closely watched by the bandit Peppino and an informant within the bank. Setting off from Rome by carriage soon afterward, he is ambushed on the road, forced from his carriage, and marched into the catacombs, where he is imprisoned by the notorious bandit chief Luigi Vampa.",
  "115": "Held captive underground, Danglars finds his money and papers untouched, which reassures him that he is merely being held for ransom. However, when he asks for food, his captor Peppino informs him that even a simple meal costs an outrageous, ever-multiplying sum, forcing the increasingly desperate and hungry Danglars to sign away portions of his fortune just to eat a single fowl.",
  "116": "As his imprisonment continues, Danglars grows steadily weaker from hunger while the bandits keep charging him exorbitant, escalating prices for food and water, draining his fortune to almost nothing. Reduced to genuine desperation and starvation, he finally begs for mercy and expresses real repentance for the wrongs of his past, at which point his hooded captor reveals himself to be Edmond Dantès, forgives him, restores his last remaining funds, and orders his release, though the ordeal leaves Danglars's hair turned entirely white.",
  "117": "On the appointed day, Maximilian Morrel arrives at the Island of Monte Cristo believing he will finally be allowed to die as promised, still consumed by grief for Valentine. Monte Cristo leads him into his lavish underground retreat and, honoring their pact, gives him a substance Morrel believes will be fatal; as Morrel loses consciousness, Valentine is revealed to be alive and standing before him, and Monte Cristo explains how he orchestrated her survival and apparent death all along. Overjoyed, the reunited couple learn that Monte Cristo has bestowed his fortune and properties upon them, and as dawn breaks he departs by sea with Haydée, who has confessed her love for him, leaving behind a letter urging the young couple to live by the wisdom that all human wisdom is contained in the words \"wait and hope.\""
};
